<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry on Abkhazia Peacekeeping Role </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry on Abkhazia Peacekeeping Role </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506133194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1214 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506133194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By diplomatic correspondent Boris Krivoshey] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 15 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- The peacekeeping 
operation in Abkhazia can begin only after a positive decision 
to that effect is made by the Federation Council of the Russian 
Federal Assembly. This view was expressed at a briefing today by 
Mikhail Demurin, deputy head of the press and information 
department of the Russian Federation Foreign Ministry. 
  He said that a reconnaissance group of generals and officers 
from the Russian Defense Ministry has been in Abkhazia since 14 
June with the aim of organizing the deployment of a Russian 
contingent which would be part of the joint peacekeeping forces 
in the Abkhaz- Georgian conflict zone. 
  "Analysis of the situation has shown that any further delays 
in the deployment of peacekeeping forces may lead to 
unpredictable consequences," Mikhail Demurin said. 

</TEXT>

