<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   India Considers Buying Russian SU-30 Fighters </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    India Considers Buying Russian SU-30 Fighters </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606113694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1101 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606113694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Alexey Kuznetsov] </F>
  [Text] New Delhi June 16 TASS -- India is looking into the 
possibility of buying a batch of Russian SU-30 fighter planes. 
A high-ranking delegation from India's military department, 
headed by Air Force Vice-Marshal Krishnaswami, has already 
departed for Russia, ITAR-TASS learned from a reliable source. 
  The Indian delegation intends to visit the Irkutsk aviation 
factory, which produces the SU-30 planes, and to hold several 
meetings with leaders in Russia's defence industry. Indian 
pilots will take the fighter out for a test flight, after which 
the contract negotiations will enter their final phase. 
  According to ITAR-TASS sources, Russia is ready to give 
India 
enough credits to buy 20 SU-30 fighters and to purchase a 
production license for the planes. India plans to manufacture 
them at the aviation factories in Nasik (Maharashtra State). 
This order should help India take advantage of the production 
capabilities it built up for the MiG-27 Soviet fighters-bombers, 
whose production license will soon run out. 
  Indian specialists stress that the Russian SU-30, equipped 
with all the latest technology, is as good as the American F-18 
and the European "Tornado", and is superior to the F-16 and the 
French "Mirage-2000". 
  The Russian fighter has powerful weapons: a 30-mm gun and 
ten 
rockets of various kinds. It is also equipped with the 
capability to refuel in mid-flight, which widens its ability to 
search out and destroy air and land targets. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

