<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Favors `Extraordinary' Measures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Favors `Extraordinary' Measures </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506134694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1223 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506134694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Head of Russia's Federal Counterintelligence Service 
(FCIS) Sergey Stepashin is in favor of extraordinary measures to 
combat crime. 
  Speaking at a press conference on Wednesday in 
Yuzhno-Sakhalinsk, he pointed out that "a real war of criminal 
clans is beginning in the country now. They use the most 
advanced technical means of destruction. That's why there has 
appeared an urgent necessity to adopt extraordinary measures," 
he stressed commenting the presidential decree on strengthening 
the fight against crime. 
  Asked about the situation concerning espionage, Stepashin 
said that his department is especially concerned at the activity 
of the special services of North Korea. He mentioned the recent 
deportation of five North Korean citizens from Russia who tried 
to find information on the components of nuclear weapons. 
According to Stepashin, three days ago several Korean citizens 
were detained in the Primorye Territory for similar reasons. 
  Having noted the active work of the US special service, 
Stepashin expressed his opinion that "the present level of 
openness is damaging our country." 
  On Thursday [16 Jun] Stepashin intends to visit Vladivostok 
and Nakhodka (Primorye Territory). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

