<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Calls Opposition `Criminals' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Calls Opposition `Criminals' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506163594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1348 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506163594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chechen President Dzhokhar Dudayev said there was no 
political opposition in the republic. "There is no opposition, 
just ordinary criminals protected by Russia which seeks to get 
its way in the Chechen Republic," he said in an interview with 
Interfax. 
  Asked by an Interfax correspondent about the possible aims 
of 
the Russian leadership in Chechnya, Dudayev said it was trying 
to discredit the Chechen leadership, to deteriorate the 
situation. He said Russia was also involved in terrorism, 
sabotage and provocations which Dudayev believed, according to 
plans of Russian politicians, might lead to chaos and collapse 
in Chechnya. 
  Dudayev said Russia was carrying out a policy of aggression 
against Chechnya. 
  "When did Russia put an end to the Russian-Caucasian war? I 
think, it never stopped. The present situation is just a 
continuation of it but in a more sophisticated manner," Dudayev 
said. In Chechnya, aggression, occupation, genocide and 
violence have been going on for 300 years already, he concluded. 

</TEXT>

