<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chechen Opposition Head Denies Moscow Backing </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chechen Opposition Head Denies Moscow Backing </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506185794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1537 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506185794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In Chechnya the head of the opposition Provisional 
Council has declared that the opposition in his republic does 
not enjoy support from Moscow. 
  "Time will tell whom Moscow is going to deal with in the 
future, Umar Avturkhanov told Interfax on Wednesday, but at the 
moment political or economic support for the Chechen opposition 
by Russia is out of the question." 
  He also denied reports that Ruslan Khasbulatov is the shadow 
leader of the opposition and described them as groundless 
inventions. "We ask him for advice in one way or other, because 
he is also worried about the future of his people", Avturkhanov 
said. 
  According to him, the delegation of the opposition began 
talks with Russia with the hope of working out a draft bilateral 
treaty and resolving several economic problems. 
  "We would want Russian federal government bodies to take the 
Chechen question seriously, we want every official to know that 
deciding about Chechen matters he decides about the Russian 
state system", Avturkhanov said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

