<DOCNO> FBIS4-40315 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov116_d_94013" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-116 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Khasbulatov `Shocked' by Measures Against Rebels </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Khasbulatov `Shocked' by Measures Against Rebels </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606121694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1037 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606121694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ruslan Khasbulatov expressed his condolences today 
to the families of the victims of the recent armed clashes 
between governmental troops and a militant group in Groznyy. 
  Today Interfax received a statement of Khasbulatov. For 
instance, the statement said, "I am shocked by this tragedy and 
by the fact that armored vehicles and armored equipment were 
used in the center of a densely populated city." He said it was 
inadmissible to use such extreme methods even when confronted 
with criminals if this could lead to the death of innocent 
people. 
  The armed clash took place last Sunday and Monday. The 
opposition headquarters told Interfax that the governmental 
forces had surrounded the group led by Ruslan Labazanov and 
subjected the residential areas of the district to heavy fire. 
  Such developments followed the order issued by Chechen 
Military Commander Sultan Geliskhanov on the disarmament of 
illegal military formations. 
  The opposition said that from 180 to 300 people had been 
killed during these events, most of them civilians. The 
official authorities said there were no more than ten people had 
been killed and no more than sixty wounded. 
  The opposition headquarters told Interfax that Labazanov and 
200 of his supporters had fled. Labazanov said he would enact 
what he called a bloody revenge on Chechen President Dzhokhar 
Dudayev and Military Commander Geliskhanov and on their 
relatives for the innocent people killed during these events. 

</TEXT>

