<F P=100> Moldova </F>
<H3> <TI>   Need for Constitutional Court Examined </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Need for Constitutional Court Examined </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506173694 Chisinau BASAPRESS in English 1939 GMT 11 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1506173694 </F>
<F P=104>  Chisinau BASAPRESS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Chisinau, BASAPRESS, 11/6/1994 -- After the 
Constitution is adopted, it will be necessary to inaugurate a 
Constitutional Court, declared to BASA Eugen Rusu, chairman of 
the parliamentary commission for appointments and statutes, 
mentioning that Moldova has no organ which could assure that the 
presidential decrees, governmental and other institutions' 
decisions do not violate the stipulations of the Constitution. 
He announced that between June 8th and 9th he participated, 
along with Nicolae Timofte, vice president of the Supreme Court, 
and Nicolae Uncu, vice-prosecutor of the Republic, at a seminar 
organized by the CSCE in collaboration with the Romanian 
Constitutional Court. At the Bucharest seminar, representatives 
of the constitutional courts of many European countries offered 
to give consultations on the organization of the Moldovan 
Constitutional Court. According to Rusu, the former Parliament 
elaborated a draft law on the Constitutional Court, which is to 
be sent to the Council of Europe's Commission for Democracy and 
Justice, whose headquarters are in Venice, to obtain eventual 
notification, and later to be examined by the Chisinau 
Parliament. 

</TEXT>

