<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kasymov Assails Russia's Partnership for Peace Conditions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kasymov Assails Russia's Partnership for Peace Conditions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506202294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1827 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506202294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kazakh First Deputy Defense Minister Alibek Kasymov 
told a news conference in Almaty Wednesday that the conditions 
put forward by Russia for joining the Partnership for Peace 
program were not acceptable. 
  In his opinion, "absolutely all states within the framework 
of this program will enjoy equal rights. No one must seek a 
special status." 
  The chief of the staff of the NATO forces in Europe, Peter 
Karstens who is on a visit to Kazakhstan said that "there will 
be no special status for anyone in the Partnership for Peace 
program and no exceptions are envisioned." 
  At present, Kazakhstan is developing a presentation document 
specifying aspects of the republic's membership in the program. 
The documents provides for consultations on a reduction of the 
Kazakh armed forces, their formation and development, including 
shaping up the defense budget and help in training personnel. 
  Kasymov admitted that the Kazakh Army suffered from a lack 
of 
officers, and the republic's leadership intend to create 
conditions for citizens of other states to serve in its armed 
forces. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

