Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Statement Urges DPRK To Resume Dialogue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Statement Urges DPRK To Resume Dialogue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506123094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1143 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506123094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Kulagin] </F>
  [Text] Almaty 15 June TASS -- A Kazakhstan Foreign Ministry 
statement, circulated here on Wednesday, expresses the 
Republic's concern over the situation on the Korean peninsula. 
The situation has become seriously aggravated in view of North 
Korea's decision to withdraw from the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA). 
  "Thus, another spiral has been added to the crisis which was 
brought on by that country's withdrawal from the treaty on 
non-proliferation of nuclear weapons," the statement said. 
  Actions taken by North Korea of late "do not give grounds to 
affirm that the country lacks a military nuclear programme," the 
statement stressed. 
  "Emergence of nuclear weapons in the northern part of the 
peninsula would pose a serious threat to both regional and 
global stability and security. 
  "This is why Kazakhstan, which has joined the Nuclear 
Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) as a non-nuclear state, and which 
comes out in favour of strict compliance with the NPT regime 
calls on North Korea to resume dialogue with the world community 
to avoid a further exacerbation of the situation concerning the 
nuclear problem on the peninsula", the statement said. 
  The Kazakhstan Foreign Ministry, positively appraising 
Russia's proposals to convene an international conference on 
security and on nuclear problem on the Korean peninsula, with 
the participation of North and South Korea, the United States, 
China, Japan, and Russia, as well as U.N. Security Council and 
IAEA representatives, urged all the sides concerned to show a 
constructive approach with a view to settling the situation. 

</TEXT>

