<F P=100> Kyrgyzstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Adopts New Import Duties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Adopts New Import Duties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506152694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0703 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506152694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Maynayev] </F>
  [Text] Bishkek, 15 Jun--Kirgizia [Kyrgyzstan] has adopted a 
policy of protectionism. In line with a decision by the 
republic's government that was promulgated today, import duties 
of 200-400 percent are being brought into effect on imports of 
alcohol, tobacco products, furniture, carpets, motor vehicles, 
and domestic television and radio equipment. 
  According to competent bodies, the duties will also affect 
goods brought in across the border by tourists for personal use, 
even if this is just a single item. 
  Although these measures are of a temporary nature, if the 
decision is to be believed, local businessmen make no secret of 
their concerns. Experience shows that there was nothing more 
permanent in the former Soviet Union than temporary decisions. 

</TEXT>

