<H3> <TI>   Premier Says Language Legislation Not Properly Implemented </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Premier Says Language Legislation Not Properly Implemented </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506191194 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1537 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506191194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Uzbek Prime Minister Abdulkhashim Mutalov said that 
the state language legislation was not satisfactorily 
implemented. 
  He told the commission supervising compliance with the 
legislation at its meeting in Tashkent that posters in Russian 
were still on display in many parts of Uzbekistan. 
  He criticized the ministries and agencies which had not used 
the Uzbek language in their correspondence. 
  Mutalov attributed this to the want of national pride and 
patriotism in the mentality of certain officials. 
  Under the legislation adopted in 1990 only the Uzbek is the 
national language while the Russian is regarded as the language 
of ethnic communication. People of over 100 nationalities 
reside in Uzbekistan. 

</TEXT>

