<H3> <TI>   Opposition May Delay Operation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Opposition May Delay Operation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506174094 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1600 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze has not 
ruled out that the position of the Georgian Parliament may cause 
a postponement of the introduction of Russian troops into the 
[Georgian-Abkhazian] conflict. Some of the Georgian 
parliamentary deputies assert that the Russian paratroops have 
been bought by the Abkhazians and, therefore, cannot act as 
peacekeepers. 
  [Unidentified correspondent] The peacekeeping operation in 
Abkhazia has been postponed until 26 June. This was stated by 
Shevardnadze at a meeting of the parliamentary majority before 
parliament started work. The opinion of the opposition deputies 
differs markedly from Shevardnadze's point of view about the 
introduction of peacekeeping forces into Abkhazia. 
  In an interview for Georgian television Shevardnadze 
condemned the actions of the opposition and described them as an 
attempt to wreck the peacekeeping operation. Shevardnadze 
expressed confidence in the success of the peace process, the 
first stage of which, the return of refugees to Gali Rayon, will 
begin in the next few days. 

</TEXT>

