<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Engineers To Deal With Mines in Abkhazia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Engineers To Deal With Mines in Abkhazia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506165794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1603 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506165794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 15 TASS -- Russian field engineering 
units will be brought in to demine sites in Abkhazia on 
Thursday, in accordance with the first stage of peacemaking 
operation in the area of Abkhazian-Georgian conflict. 
  The announcement was made by Colonel General Vladimir 
Semenov 
at a news conference held in the main headquarters of Russian 
land forces on Wednesday. 
  Russian peace-making forces will be introduced in the area 
in 
accordance with Georgian-Abkhazian agreements and Russian 
president's decree, Semenov emphasized. 
  According to him, at present a task force of the Russian 
Defence Ministry led by Deputy Defence Minister Colonel General 
Georgiy Kondratyev is in the area, making a reconnaisance of the 
sites where the peace-keepers will be stationed and commanding 
points will be set up. They are going to demine these very 
sites. 
  Asked if Russian servicemen will be guaranteed security, 
Semenov underlined that a full guarantee could not be given. 
The main conditions for such a guarantee lie in demining the 
terraine in the 12-kilometer strip and building engineering 
facilities at the peace- keepers' checkpoints, he added. 
  Every effort will be made to prevent losses of Russian 
servicemen, he said. 
  In case of attacks upon the checkpoints run by Russian 
peace- 
keepers, the latter will shoot to kill, he emphasized. 

</TEXT>

