<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Approves Free Trade Agreement With EU </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Cabinet Approves Free Trade Agreement With EU </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   WS1506133894 Tallinn BNS in English 1016 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS1506133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riga, Jun 15, BNS -- The Latvian Cabinet accepted 
Tuesday a free trade agreement with the European Union (EU). 
The Latvian and EU delegations plan to sign the agreement on 
June 20, the Foreign Ministry's EU Affairs State Minister 
Olgerts Pavlovskis said at a press conference. 
  Pavlovskis said that the free trade agreement with the EU is 
very important for the development of Latvia's economy. 
  Pavlovskis stressed that the agreement will not negatively 
influence Latvia's agriculture and industry, because, according 
to the initialed agreement, Latvia will have a transitional 
period for four years during which the import duty tariffs for 
the EU states' agricultural produce will be gradually decreased. 
  The Agricultural Ministry's specialists support the ready 
for 
signing additional protocols to the free trade agreement, 
providing for the procedure of decreasing of agricultural 
products' import duty tariffs, because the agreement itself 
provides for protecting Latvia's inner market from flowing in of 
too much EU agricultural products, said Pavlovskis. 
  The free trade agreement with the EU will promote the 
flowing 
in of foreign investments in Latvia and establishing of joint 
ventures with the local producers, whose produce could be sold 
in the markets of the European states. 
  Pavlovskis noted that the quota for industrial and 
agricultural produce can be revised once in three years thus 
effectively regulating the development of Latvia's foreign trade. 
  The Latvian 5th Saeima plans to accept the free trade 
agreement with the EU in October. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40356 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov116_u_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-116 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Latvia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Free Trade Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Further on Free Trade Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506200194 Riga Radio Riga Network in Latvian 2000 GMT 14 
Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506200194 </F>
<F P=104>  Riga Radio Riga Network </F>
<F P=105>  Latvian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A regular session of the Cabinet of Ministers took 
place on Tuesday [14 June]. The almost 200-page free trade 
agreement with the European Union was approved there. 
  Olgerts Pavlovskis, state minister for foreign trade and 
European Union affairs, tells us the following about it: 
  [Begin Pavlovskis recording] The cabinet approved the free 
trade agreement concluded with the European Union and authorized 
the Latvian delegation to sign it in Brussels on (?20) June. 
  That was a long and very interesting and intensive way. This 
document is heavy and [word indistinct] -- both in the sphere of 
Latvian politics and the sphere of the Latvian economy. 
  In this agreement -- we often hear that agriculture will be 
destroyed, industry will be destroyed, and so on. Various 
mechanisms, various protection mechanisms so to speak, which 
will protect not only industrial (products), (when) some sort of 
a critical situation comes about, for example, in a newly 
created sector of industry, but also in agriculture, have also 
been [word indistinct] in this agreement. 
  We have opened the door for Latvian goods to the West. We 
cannot guarantee that the goods will be bought, we cannot 
guarantee the market, but at least we have created conditions in 
which Latvian producers and Latvian farmers will be able to sell 
their products in the West with reduced tariffs. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

