<F P=100> Lithuania </F>
<H3> <TI>   Five New Ministers Sworn In </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Five New Ministers Sworn In </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506150994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1258 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506150994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladas Burbulis] </F>
  [Text] Vilnius June 15 TASS -- Lithuanian parliament 
speaker Ceslovas Jursenas swore in five new ministers at the 
morning session of the Lithuanian Sejm on Wednesday. 
  Three of them will be put in charge of absolutely new 
governmental departments founded in accordance with the law on 
cabinet activities. Namely, Bronis Bradauskas will be from now 
on minister of environmental protection; Vladislavas Domarkas - 
minister of science and education (until recently he was deputy 
foreign minister); and Dainius Trinkunas - minister of culture 
(previously, he was at the head of Ministry of Culture and 
Public Education). In accordance with the above-mentioned law, 
there will be two separate respective ministries from now on. 
  Another two newly sworn-in ministers stepped in the shoes of 
their predecessors. Sylviculturist Albertas Vasilyauskas will 
be minister of forestry and his namesake Aleksandras will be 
minister of economics. 
  Almost all of the new ministers are either members or 
supporters of the ruling Democratic Party of Labour. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

