<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Economic Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reform Center Leaders Say Inflation Stable </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reform Center Leaders Say Inflation Stable </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506173594 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1600 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506173594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Vesti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] The state of affairs in Russia's economy is normal 
and whatever kind of market has been formed, the state's 
intervention in market relations has been minimal. This was 
stated today at a news conference by the heads of the 
government's Economic Reform Center. According to them, 
inflation over the last couple of months has remained at a low 
level -- 8 percent. However, there are certain trends toward it 
increasing. The ruble has been losing its value at a slower 
rate than prices have been rising, and the average wage has 
moved closer -- calculated in foreign currency -- to $100. 
  Meanwhile, according to the Economic Reform Center, there 
remains a considerable fall in output in the machine-building 
and fuel and power complex. The failure of enterprises to make 
payments are not too good, either. Their debts on wages remain 
high. However, according to Richard Yard, an economist from 
Britain, this type of nonpayment was reduced by 4 percent 
compared with April. Moreover, according to Yard, the overdue 
debts of enterprises are lower than the European average. The 
London economist noted that in the sphere of employment among 
the Russian population, as nowhere else in the world, the 
redistribution of the working people in production outstrips 
open unemployment. And the latter in our country increased by 
only 1 percent during the past 18 months. 
  The most comforting news was given by Sergey Pavlenko, a 
spokesman for the Economic Reform Center. Among the population, 
faith in financial institutions has increased. The citizens' 
savings are growing not in hard currency, but in rubles. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

