<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military, Nuclear &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   ITAR-TASS Reports Parameters of Foton Satellite </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ITAR-TASS Reports Parameters of Foton Satellite </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506134294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0650 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 15 Jun--Another artificial Earth satellite, 
Foton, designed for continued study of the properties of 
materials in space, was launched on 14 June 1994 from the 
Plesetsk cosmodrome by means of a Soyuz booster rocket. 
  Its 18-day flight program envisages experiments on the 
production of semiconductors, optical glass with a variable 
refractive index, and biologically active substances in 
microgravitation, as well as the development of technologies for 
their experimental industrial production. 
  In accordance with a commercial agreement, a Biopan 
container 
with equipment designed by German specialists has been placed on 
board the Foton satellite. 
  The satellite has been placed in orbit with the following 
parameters: 
  --initial period of revolution--90.4 mins; 
  --apogee--385 km; 
  --perigee--229 km; 
  --orbital inclination 62.8 degrees. 
  The apparatus on board the satellite is working normally. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40383 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov116_b_94028" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-116 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military, Nuclear &amp; Space Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Minister on Nuclear Power Expansion </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Deputy Minister on Nuclear Power Expansion </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506183594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1537 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506183594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] By the year 2010 the share of electricity generated 
at nuclear power stations in Russia will grow to 30 or 35 
percent compared to 14 percent last year. These figures were 
disclosed at a Wednesday news conference in Moscow by the Deputy 
Minister of Nuclear Energy Lev Ryabev. 
  According to the official, nuclear power engineering is 
going 
to expand as the production of oil and coal is going to decline; 
experts predict that only gas extraction is going to grow: from 
620 billion cubic meters now to 780 billion in 2010. 
  Between 2001 and 2009 Russia will shut down all nuclear 
power 
plants of the first generation. All of them were designed 
before 1973 and do not meet modern safety norms. Such 
generators are located at the Leningrad, Kursk, Novovoronezh and 
Kola stations. 
  Ryabev said that power units of the third generation are now 
being developed and are equipped with safety systems which do 
not rely on human actions. The first power station of the third 
generation should be built in 2000 or 2002. 
  The ministry is also working on reactors of the fourth 
generation which according to Ryabev will be based on principles 
of "natural safety." These plants would be designed so that no 
escape of radiation is possible under any condition, the 
minister said. 
  Russia is determined to develop a closed production circuit 
in nuclear power engineering: Usable uranium will be extracted 
from used fuel and most of the highly active wastes burned in 
fast reactors. 
  Ryabev stressed that Russia has enough nuclear fuel to last 
till the year 2020 and the uranium ore extracted in the Chita 
Region is being exported. He said the ministry is open to the 
question of changing forms of ownership. "So far nuclear 
facilities are government property, but we are not ruling out 
the possibility that they can be turned into joint-stock 
companies or sold to private owners," Ryabev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

