<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Envoy Says Dialogue, Sanctions Incompatible </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Envoy Says Dialogue, Sanctions Incompatible </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506142194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1301 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Aleksandr Krylovich] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 15 Jun (ITAR-TASS) -- The introduction of 
any sanctions at all against Pyongyang and the holding of an 
international conference on the problem of the Korean 
peninsula's nuclear-free status are incompatible. This point of 
view was expressed today by DPRK Ambassador to Moscow Son 
Song-pil. 
  Replying to an ITAR-TASS correspondent's question, he said: 
"At one time we displayed an interest in the Russian proposal to 
hold an international conference. Our side based its position 
on the fact that such a forum would promote a solution to the 
accumulated problems around the negotiating table on the basis 
of equal rights and mutual respect. There was no question of 
any sanctions at that time. Now we clearly state: Sanctions and 
dialogue are incompatible." 
  Regarding the DPRK's departure from the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA), the ambassador announced that on 13 June 
his government officially informed the U.S. Administration of 
this, the latter being the depository state of the IAEA Charter. 
He stressed that recently all the cooperation with the IAEA 
boiled down to carrying out inspections of North Korean 
facilities which were of a "far from objective nature". The 
IAEA has practically neither the time nor the inclination for 
constructive cooperation in the development of the DPRK's 
peaceful nuclear program as envisioned by the charter of that 
organization, the diplomat said, . 
  "The longer we stayed in the IAEA the more vigorously our 
peaceful nuclear activity was being restricted," Son Song-pil 
stated. He considers that the resolution recently adopted at 
the Council of Administrators of the IAEA on the "North Korean 
nuclear problem" effectively signifies the introduction of 
sanctions. This, in his opinion, is what forced the DPRK 
Government to make the decision to leave the international 
agency. 
  As for the Treaty of Nonproliferation of Nuclear Weapons, 
the 
ambassador said the DPRK reserved the right to so-called 
"special status". This is because his country announced its 
departure from the treaty but then declared its "temporary 
suspension." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

