<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Criticizes UN Draft Resolution on Korea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Criticizes UN Draft Resolution on Korea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606113094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1018 
GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1606113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Dmitriy Gorokhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 16 Jun -- Minister of Foreign Affairs of the 
Russian Federation Andrey Kozyrev today levelled criticism at 
the Security Council draft resolution released by the American 
delegation to the United Nations, on a settlement of the 
situation on the Korean peninsula. In his words, the draft 
resolution contravenes the accords reached in the course of the 
conversations beteen the presidents of Russia and the United 
States. 
  One can only express perplexity at the fact, he said, that 
"the American diplomats have released in New York a draft 
resolution containing a list of specific sanctions." Andrey 
Kozyrev said this was done by the American side despite the fact 
that during the telephone conversation between Presidents Boris 
Yeltsin and Bill Clinton, and then during the Russian Federation 
foreign minister's telephone conversation with U.S. Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher "it was agreed absolutely clearly to 
act jointly, to work out a draft resolution jointly and not to 
put forward unilateral unitiatives." 
  "The release of such a draft resolution unilaterally will 
cause us serious difficulty in examining this document," A. 
Kozyrev stated. "We will not in any event support the range of 
sanctions which is being put forward without previous agreement 
with us." 
  For its part, Moscow, as indeed the heads of the two states 
agreed, A. Kozyrev announced, conveyed confidentially to the 
American side its own proposals on a draft resolution. They 
include both the idea of sanctions and specific ideas on an 
international conference on questions of security and the 
nuclear-free status of the Korean peninsula. In keeping with 
the accords of the presidents and of the heads of the foreign 
policy deparltments of the Russian Federation and the United 
States, in the resolution both these elements should be 
contained on an equal footing. 
  Expressing the opinion that "the work will be continued," A. 
Kozyrev at the same time stressed that "the unilateral actions 
of the American diplomats in New York only complicate the 
matter." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

