<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Sanctions `Last Resort' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Says Sanctions `Last Resort' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506131394 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1219 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506131394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev said today 
that North Korea must respect the treaty on non-proliferation of 
nuclear weapons. 
  He said in an interview that he had information proving that 
North Korea had prepared a statement on withdrawal from 
International Atomic Energy Agency. However, the secretariat of 
the agency has as yet received no similar official statement. 
  Kozyrev underlined that if North Korea violated the Non- 
Proliferation Treaty, there would be no other way out but to 
impose sanctions. Kozyrev pointed out that the sanctions must 
be imposed gradually and be considered a last resort. 
  Kozyrev spoke in favor of an international conference 
initiated by Russia so that China, Japan, Korea, Russia, the 
U.S.A., France, Britain and other members of the UN Security 
Council could make the issue clear for themselves since North 
Korea had put forward a number of explanations of its position. 
  Kozyrev emphasized that North Korea must continue to 
participate in the Non-Proliferation Treaty and observe the 
conditions put forward by the International Atomic Energy Agency. 

</TEXT>

