<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Continues Visit to Amur, Tuva Regions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin Continues Visit to Amur, Tuva Regions </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Arrives in Tuva </H4>

<F P=102> LD1506191894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1403 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506191894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents Tamara Zamyatina and Yevgeniy </F>
Sovetskiy] 
  [Text] Tuva, 15 Jun -- The Russian president today arrived 
in Kyzyl, the capita of Tuva, from Blagoveshchensk, and has 
called for Russia's economic and social problems to be solved by 
the combined efforts of the center and the regions. 
  Before meeting Boris Yeltsin, Kaadyr-ool Bichelday, chairman 
of the Tuva Republic's parliament, told an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent that the local authorities and population expect 
understanding of the region's special character to be shown 
during the visit. The leaders are counting on the president 
helping to solve the republic's transport problems. "If life in 
Tuva used to be dependent on vehicle wheels, then that has now 
changed to steamship propellers, since the use of wheels would 
mean doubling the costs of cargo transportation," Kaadyr-ool 
Bicheldey said. 
  Bicheldey sees Yeltsin's visit to the republic as a 
continuation of the policy of passing control over both the 
economy and politics from the state to the regions. Here, the 
parliamentary chairman described the existing contradictions 
between the constitutions of Russia and Tuva as "a matter to be 
agreed upon." 

</TEXT>

