<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry on `Great Concern' Over DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry on `Great Concern' Over DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506132194 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1210 
GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1506132194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Itar-Tass diplomatic correspondent Boris Krivoshey] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 15 June -- The DPRK's departure from the 
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has been received with 
great concern in Russia. This was stated at a briefing today by 
Mikhail Demurin, deputy head of administration of the 
Information and Press Department of the Russian Federation 
Foreign Ministry . 
  "Our fundamental position is well known and remains 
immutable. Russia favors strengthening the regime of 
nonproliferation of nuclear weapons and favors transparency of 
nuclear programs so that no doubts or fears will arise 
concerning the possibility of attempts to create nuclear 
weaponry. It is especially important that a state which is a 
member of the treaty and which has an agreement with the IAEA on 
guarantees should honestly and consistently fulfill its 
obligations. If this has not been done or is not being done, 
then the international community has the right to react 
appropriately," the Russian diplomat said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40408 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov116_a_94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-116 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

