<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Withdrawal From IAEA Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Withdrawal From IAEA Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506160094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1348 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506160094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia is deeply concerned over the withdrawal of 
North Korea from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA). 
  "Our principal position is well known and remains the same. 
Russia stands for a stronger non-proliferation regime and for 
transparent nuclear programs so that there be no fear of 
possible attempts to create nuclear weapons," Russian Foreign 
Ministry Spokesman Mikhail Demurin said at a briefing in Moscow 
today. 
  He said it was especially important that a state 
participating in the non-proliferation treaty and in an 
agreement with the IAEA fulfill its obligations. "If this was 
not done or is not done, the world community has the right to an 
adequate response," Demurin said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40409 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov116_a_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-116 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Comments </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Official Comments </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506162794 Moscow NTV in Russian 1500 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506162794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NTV </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mikhail Beliy, director of the First Asia Department 
in the Foreign Ministry, in an interview today to our television 
company, told us about Russia's reaction to N. Korea's 
withdrawal from the IAEA. 
  [Begin Beliy recording] We are not inclined to dramatize the 
DPRK's Announced withdrawal from the IAEA since we proceed from 
the basis that the DPRK remains a participant-member of the Non- 
Proliferation Treaty, and therefore has an agreement with the 
IAEA within the framework of that treaty. Therefore, 
inspections of nuclear sites in the DPRK should continue. 
  We are in close contact with the other five permanent 
members 
of the UN Security Council and we are beginning to prepare a 
draft resolution. An agreement has been reached that, in the 
very near future, the Russian foreign minister and the U.S. 
secretary of state will meet. [end recording] 
  Russia believes that tough UN sanctions against the DPRK is 
an extreme measure. However, if there is going to be talk of 
sanctions, then Russia will insist that they must be gradual and 
also take into account its own interests. 

</TEXT>

