<H3> <TI>   Stepashin on PRC, DPRK Operations in Far East </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Stepashin on PRC, DPRK Operations in Far East </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1606093894 Vladivostok Radio Vladivostok Network in 
Russian 0210 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1606093894 </F>
<F P=104>  Vladivostok Radio Vladivostok Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Lunch Hour Break" program] </F>
  [Text] Sergey Stepashin, director of the Federal 
Counterintelligence Service [FSK], who is touring the Far East, 
today gave a news conference in Vladivostok. Stepashin gave the 
reasons for his Far East tour as: The increased 
counterintelligence activities of the Japanese, North Korean, 
and Chinese intelligence services in this region of Russia; the 
upcoming Federation Council discussions on Russian border 
issues; and to get acquainted with working conditions in 
regional FSK departments to find out how the Russian president's 
edict on combating organized crime and banditry will be 
implemented in practice. 
  According to the FSK director, the Chinese and North Korean 
intelligence services are actively recruiting people, and 
studying military technology and the drug business in the Far 
East territory. 
  Stepashin also said the document on joint action to 
implement 
the president's edict on combating organized crime will soon be 
signed with the Russian Internal Affairs Ministry. In the FSK 
director's opinion, this edict is very tough and even disagrees 
with some statutes of Russian law, but it is extremely necessary 
given current conditions. The document specifically permits not 
only lengthening the period of investigation, but also gives the 
right to legalize operational and technical information and hand 
it over to the court. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

