<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Vo Van Kiet on Prospects For Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Vo Van Kiet on Prospects For Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606123294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1201 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606123294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Sergey Bychkov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 16 TASS -- Vietnamese Prime Minister Vo 
Van Kiet remains optimistic about prospects of signing a 
bilateral treaty with Russia. "Talks with the Russian side are 
going on productively. The new interstate treaty has been in 
general agreed upon which is very important", he told TASS on 
Thursday and added that the document would be signed after 
certain improvements. 
  The treaty was scheduled to be signed today. However, the 
delegations failed to eliminate various disagreements, TASS 
learned from sources close to the Russian Government. 
  Sources from the Vietnamese delegation explained to TASS 
that 
the disputed issues include prospecting and production of oil 
and natural gas by the joint "Vietsovpetro" venture, the 
problems of the Vietnamese community in Russia, as well as the 
Russian naval base in Cam Ranh. Vietnam wants to revise its 
leasing terms. Besides, agreement is yet to be reached on the 
role of the United Nations in the world and the Vietnamese debt 
to Russia. 

</TEXT>

