<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Reports Plan To Visit Crimea </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Reports Plan To Visit Crimea </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506124594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1044 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506124594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk intends to visit 
Crimea and, in particular, those regions of the peninsula which 
have suffered from the drought. 
  At a press conference held on his return from Luxembourg on 
Tuesday, Kravchuk reported that during this trip he intends to 
determine the scale of the aid which Kiev would render to Crimea. 
  Speaking about the present conflict between Kiev and 
Simferopol, Kravchuk said that Crimea would be gradually 
introduced into Ukraine's "constitutional regime" by means of 
reasonable compromises but not by force. 
  Kravchuk said there would be no coercive measures with 
respect to Crimea in the future and stressed that "Ukraine will 
never overstep this threshold and will not allow anybody to do 
this." 
  Kravchuk underlined that in accordance with the treaty on 
partnership and cooperation between Ukraine and European Union 
signed by him on Tuesday in Luxembourg, the European Union 
expresses its support to Ukraine's territorial integrity and 
sovereignty. 
  "Europe recognizes that this is a factor of European 
stability," Kravchuk said. 

</TEXT>

