<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Working Group Insists on Further Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Working Group Insists on Further Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1506153594 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 14 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> AU1506153594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "The Draft Agreement Is Ready"] </F>
  [Text] On Friday night [10 June], a delegation of the 
Crimean parliament handed a draft agreement between Ukraine and 
the Crimea to the Ukrainian side. The negotiations between 
representatives of the sides within the framework of the 
interparliamentary Ukrainian-Crimean working group were 
completed in Simferopol. 
  As the agency INTERFAX-UKRAYINA was informed by the head of 
the Crimean delegation and representative of the parliamentary 
Commission for Legislation and Law Enforcement, Sergey Nikulin, 
the draft consists of three parts: Powers that the Crimea hands 
over to Ukraine; powers that Ukraine may hand over to the 
Crimea; and joint powers. However, he did not specify the 
content of those parts. 
  According to S. Nikulin, during the scheduled round of talks 
"the sides did not even try to discuss those articles of the 
Crimean Constitution that did not suit Ukraine." The Crimean 
delegation, he said, stated directly and unambiguously: There 
will be no revision of the Crimean Constitution. 
  The working group believes that just the first stage has 
been 
completed and insists that work be continued. 

</TEXT>

