<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radioactivity `Due to Presence of Cesium' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radioactivity `Due to Presence of Cesium' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1606104094 Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY in Ukrainian 16 Jun 94 p 4 </F>
<F P=103> AU1606104094 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev HOLOS UKRAYINY </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Two unattributed reports: "A Leak Has Been Revealed at the </F>
Chernobyl Atomic Electric Power Plant"] 
  [Text] On 7 June, a water leak from the second power 
unit's decay tank, where cassettes with used-up fuel are stored, 
was revealed at the Chernobyl Atomic Electric Power Plant [AES]. 
Head of the Chernobyl AES shift Oleksandr Yelchyshchev informed 
the INTERFAX-UKRAINE Agency that the leak amounts to two cubic 
meters per hour. He pointed out that this has not led to a 
change in the radiation situation in adjacent buildings. 
  According to him, the water leak does not constitute any 
special danger. O. Yelchyshchev also stressed that such 
incidents are "a disease of all atomic plants of this type." 
<H8>  * * * </H8>
  As reported yesterday [14 June] by Ukraine's State Committee 
for Atomic Supervision, at the second power unit of the 
Chernobyl AES, beside the main system for adding water to the 
decay tank, where there were 480 cassettes, three additional 
ones have been prepared. Collection and purification of water 
that percolates through walls and ceilings of several chambers 
adjacent to the decay tank have been organized. The 
radioactivity of this water is about 1.0 microcurie per liter. 
It is mainly due to the presence of cesium. 
  A program has been elaborated for locating the leak, and 
work 
is based upon that program. In particular, 420 nuclear 
cassettes have been taken out of the tank. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40437 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov116_f_94015" </HT>


