<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin To Aid Russians in Near-Abroad </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Yeltsin To Aid Russians in Near-Abroad </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1706061094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 17 Jun 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK1706061094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [INTERFAX report under the "In Brief" rubric: "Aid Program"] </F>
  [Text] Russian President Yeltsin is apparently to 
promulgate, before the end of June, a program of aid to Russians 
living in the states of "near-abroad." This is expected to take 
place during an official meeting in the Kremlin with 
representatives of power structures and public associations, 
Abdulakh Mikitayev, chairman of the commission on questions of 
citizenship under the Russian Federation president, has 
announced. The program, he said, would incorporate three edicts 
already drafted by the commission he heads. The principal edict 
is entitled "On the Concept of Russian Federation Policy in 
Regard to Fellow Countrymen Living Abroad." Mr. Mikitayev 
pointed out that a package of documents on a mechanism of 
putting the edicts into effect will be up for approval. The 
government is completing work on this package. The draft law 
"On the Concept," according to A. Mikitayev, proclaims Russia's 
initiative to formalize at an interstate level measures that 
would guarantee the observance of the rights of nonindigenous 
populations permanently resident in new independent states. The 
two other draft edicts envisage specific aid to retired 
servicemen resident in the Baltic states. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

