<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin Doubts Economic Figures </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin Doubts Economic Figures </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606170494 Moscow NTV in Russian 1500 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606170494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NTV </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Video report by correspondent Aleksandr Shashkov] </F>
  [Text] Russian Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, opening 
today's Russian government session, was strict as usual. He 
began by removing two questions from the agenda since Cabinet 
members had not had time to acquaint themselves with them, and 
by recognizing as correct the criticism of the government 
expressed by the president at a news conference. 
  The report by the deputy minister of economics on the 
preliminary results of the first six months of this year 
bristled with figures. On the basis of them, Yakov Urinson drew 
the conclusion that the government program for stabilizing the 
situation in the economy is beginning to bring real positive 
results, and that any talk of the collapse of the economy or of 
it being on the brink of collapse is groundless. 
  Without denying the claims of the Economics Ministry, Viktor 
Chernomyrdin nevertheless cast doubt on the figures on which 
they are based. As it turned out, statistics today follow the 
imprecision of the statistics of the Soviet Union, with the 
difference that if previously the indices received by the State 
Committee for Statistics were exaggerated in the name of the 
transient red banner, then now they are underestimated in order 
to avoid taxes, which also confirms the movement of the economy 
toward market relations. 

</TEXT>

