<H3> <TI>   Banks Ask Foreign Partners for `Moratorium' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Banks Ask Foreign Partners for `Moratorium' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1706063094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 17 Jun 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK1706063094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Sergey Rybak report under the "In Brief" rubric: "Russian </F>
Banks Ask for Respite"] 
  [Text] The Association of Russian Banks [ARB], in the 
person of its president Mr. Yegorov, at a news briefing 
yesterday, asked their foreign partners to call a moratorium on 
their activities in Russia until 1 January 1996, the date 
determined by the presidential edict of 23 November 1993. This 
request is motivated by the inability of 75 percent of newly 
formed Russian commercial banks to compete owing mainly to the 
generally low qualification of their staffs. At the same time 
Mr. Yegorov noted the need for all-out support for banks with 
mixed capital. The ARB president made his statement in the 
presence of the heads of Moscow City's major banks "Stolichnyy," 
"Menatep," and "Mostbank." 

</TEXT>

