<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Atomic Energy Minister: West Trying to Discredit Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Atomic Energy Minister: West Trying to Discredit Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606120094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1037 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606120094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Reports about the outflow of nuclear materials from 
Russia have the sole goal of proving that the presence of 
nuclear weapons in Russia is dangerous to the world community 
and that Russia should be relieved of this burden, Russia's 
First Deputy Minister for Atomic Energy Lev Ryabev told INTERFAX. 
  These reports also reflect the ongoing struggle for the 
markets of nuclear expertise, he said. Some western countries 
have concentrated their attention on the traditionally Russian 
markets and are trying to discredit Russian science and 
industrial and nuclear potential. 
  He said that out of the 10 cases of theft of nuclear 
materials over the past 18 months, nine involved depleted 
uranium-238 which cannot be used for making a nuclear bomb. 
  He announced that highly enriched uranium-235 was stolen 
only 
once at the research center Luch in a Moscow suburb, when one 
staff member managed to steal about one and a half kilograms of 
this material. 
  "But even this amount is insufficient for making a bomb," 
said Ryabev. No other instances of theft of nuclear materials 
which can be used in nuclear weapons have been registered, he 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

