<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Committee Chief: Crime Edict Violates Constitution </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Committee Chief: Crime Edict Violates Constitution </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1606082594 Moscow PRAVDA in Russian 16 Jun 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK1606082594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow PRAVDA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Valentina Nikiforova and Pavel Filippov: "In </F>
Circumvention of the Constitution. The Presidential Edict Is 
More Ado About Crime"] 
  [Excerpts] On 14 June President Boris Yeltsin signed an 
edict "On Urgent Measures to Protect the Population Against 
Gangsterism and Other Manifestations of Organized Crime." It 
talks in particular about enacting a system of urgent measures 
to combat it. Primarily total -- including criminal prosecution 
-- investigation not only of suspects but also their relatives, 
friends, and other individuals and corporate entities. [passage 
omitted] 
  Here is how the edict was assessed by Duma Security 
Committee 
Chairman Viktor Ilyukhin: 
  "The first impression: The mere fact of signing such an 
edict is a gross violation of the Constitution, a departure from 
criminal law procedures and substantive criminal law norms, and 
a violation of human rights and freedoms. The president has 
once again shown that he has not observed and is not going to 
observe the Constitution -- even the one that he drafted and 
spent enormous efforts to have approved. 
  "Second: Under normal conditions this regime cannot function 
or stand up to crime. In the end, nothing prevented the 
president from inviting the Duma to draft and approve a law to 
fight crime. And the situation would have changed drastically. 
In that event this struggle would be based on a clear-cut legal 
foundation. But no matter what may be said in presidential and 
government structures, there have been no results. And the 
edict is just a warning to criminals: Be more careful." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40471 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov117_c_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-117 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Committee Says Edict Unconstitutional </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Security Committee Says Edict Unconstitutional </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606174494 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1600 GMT 
16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1606174494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The State Duma's Security Committee has unanimously 
described the Russian president's edict on urgent measures to 
protect the population from gangsterism and other manifestations 
of organized crime as contradicting the Constitution and 
existing legislation. This was stated on Thursday in an 
interview to Interfax by Viktor Ilyukhin. He noted that this 
fact was reflected in the State Duma's decision, which had been 
prepared on this matter. 
  The lower chamber plans to discuss the president's edict at 
a 
plenary meeting on Friday 17 June. Ilyukhin stressed that in 
conditions when the Constitutional Court is temporarily not 
operating, only the president can halt the operation of the 
edict. A recommendation to Boris Yeltsin to do this is also set 
out in the draft State Duma decision. 

</TEXT>

