<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Mayor Supports Edict on Organized Crime </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Mayor Supports Edict on Organized Crime </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606145494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1348 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606145494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Sugak] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 16 TASS -- Moscow Mayor Yuriy Luzhkov 
has qualified the Russian president's decree on urgent measures 
for the defence of the population from bandits and other forms 
of organised crime as a very important and timely measure. 
Luzhkov pointed out that an extremely tense criminal situation 
in the country and ways out of it are the most important 
problems faced by the city today. 
  He pointed out that the situation in the city had acquired 
an 
entirely different character by now. Earlier, mafia structures 
used to settle scores between themselves, building up tension in 
the city without directly affecting the life of city residents, 
whereas today, the level of criminal activities not only 
expanded in scope, but acquired an entirely different quality. 
It affects major businessmen, bankers and other business people 
who are involved in the formation of new economy in the city. 
  A recent statement made by the board of the "Logovaz" joint 
stock society in connection with an attempt on the life of its 
director general has exasperated the city authorities, Luzhkov 
said. Apart from prominent activists, major state and 
commercial agents, common people die, who have nothing to do 
with this but and who happened to be on the scene of the tragedy. 
  "To transfer the police to a reinforced system of 
maintenance 
of law and order - this is what the new decree provides for," 
the mayor said. He pointed out that the city is prepared to 
meet the interests of the most important department for ensuring 
the city's well-being as never before: police stations are 
being provided with new premises and funds are being allocated, 
including hard currency, to provide the police with the 
necessary facilities and equipment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

