<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Police Continue Subway Operation Against Drugs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow Police Continue Subway Operation Against Drugs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1506161694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1515 GMT 15 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1506161694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Kulikov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 15 TASS -- Moscow's police continue the 
operation code-named "Mak" (Poppy) on the Moscow metro in an 
attempt to curb the rising wave of crime in the Russian capital. 
  Over the two weeks since the beginning of the operation, the 
police have seized over 20 kilograms of drugs. 
  On Tuesday, on one of the metro stations they detained a 
resident of Tajikistan who was carrying one kilogram of opium. 
An investigation was launched. 
  The operation is generally viewed as part of the federal 
anti-crime programme approved by the president. The government 
plans to spend about five trillion roubles to implement it, 
hoping to receive back twice as much. 
  The programme largely expands the rights of law enforcement 
bodies and provides for a greater role of counterintelligence in 
fighting organised crime in Russia. Counterintelligence service 
leaders said they will set up a special body to take active 
measures to combat the rising wave of crime and will act in 
cooperation with other crime-fighting organisations. Similar 
bodies are planned to be set up in several big Russian cities, 
including Moscow, St. Petersburg and Novosibirsk. 
  On Tuesday, President Boris Yeltsin signed a decree giving 
Russia's police new powers to fight organised crime which has 
been lately terrorizing most Russian cities. 
  To prevent possible criticism of the decree, a high-ranking 
Russian counterintelligence official said earlier today that the 
decree does not infringe upon civil right and curbs only the 
rights of criminal groupings. Yevgeniy Sevostyanov, head of the 
counterintelligence service in Moscow and the Moscow region, 
said that the decree aims at protecting the population of Russia 
from organised crime. "The adopted measures limit only the 
rights of the members of criminal gangs and their direct 
accomplices," he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40483 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov117_d_94011" </HT>


