<F P=100> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   India Interested in Tajik Dialogue on Reconciliation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    India Interested in Tajik Dialogue on Reconciliation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706091894 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0422 
GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706091894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondent Leonid Kotov] </F>
  [Text] Delhi, 17 June -- India is seriously interested in a 
dialogue between the Government of Tajikistan and opposition 
groupings on national reconciliation, which is being conducted 
at the United Nation's initiative. However, the Indian 
Government has decided to leave open the issue of its 
participation alongside with Pakistan and Iran as an observer at 
these talks, a regular round of which will take place in 
Islamabad soon. 
  Salman Khurshid, Indian minister of state for external 
affairs, stated this position of the Republic during his visit 
to Tajikistan, Kazakhstan, and Kyrgyzstan. An ITAR-TASS 
correspondent was informed by sources in the Indian Ministry of 
External Affairs that the minister of state informed Prime 
Minister P. V. Narasimha Rao in detail about the results of his 
talks with the leaders of the central Asian countries and in 
particular about the situation on the Tajik-Afghan border. In 
the opinion of sources at the Indian Ministry of External 
Affairs, the situation on the border between Tajikistan and 
Afghanistan will be discussed during the upcoming visit of the 
head of the Indian government to the Russian Federation 29 
June-2 July. 
  India intends to maintain close contacts with all the 
participants in the inter-Tajik through its embassy in Dushanbe 
talks because it is very concerned about the situation on the 
border between Tajikistan and Afghanistan. In New Delhi's 
opinion, it influences the situation in the entire region and 
can affect India's security, which is anxious that the conflict 
in Tajikistan not become threatening and not become a repeat of 
the bloody Afghan war. 
  Nevertheless, representatives of the Republic's Ministry of 
External Affairs stressed that India's official participation in 
the talks between the Tajik Government and opposition as an 
observer is deemed inexpedient as such a precedent may lead to 
Pakistan intensifying its demands to be included in possible 
talks between the Indian Government and Muslim political 
groupings on normalizing the situation in Jammu and Kashmir. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40494 </DOCNO>
