Daily Report 
<DATE1>  16 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Laws on Exit-Entry, Identity Cards Approved </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Laws on Exit-Entry, Identity Cards Approved </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   MK1606121094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 16 Jun 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> MK1606121094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under the "NEGA Reports" rubric] </F>
  [Text] The republic's parliament has approved two draft 
laws on entering and exiting the country, and on identity cards 
for citizens of Azerbaijan. Under the "entry and exit" law, 
exit is restricted for those convicted of crimes, under 
investigation, or drafted for military service, as well as for 
persons under obligations not to divulge state secrets. Three 
types of external passports have been approved: civilian, 
service, and diplomatic. The law on identity cards for citizens 
of the republic calls for two types of identity cards: for 
those under 16, and for those past that age. The plastic cards 
will include the name in full, nationality, age, marital status, 
eligibility for military service, and a photograph. All the 
information on the cards will be put in a unified bank of data 
about the country's citizens open for use by the republic's 
Ministry of Internal Affairs, Ministry of National Security, and 
Ministry of Foreign Affairs. The introduction of identity cards 
will be financed from the budget at a total cost of nearly six 
million manats. All passports of the former USSR are supposed 
to be replaced by identity cards before the end of 1996. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

