<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plyushch Comments on Masol Election, Kravchuk Leadership </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Plyushch Comments on Masol Election, Kravchuk Leadership </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706133694 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1130 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1706133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Poltava [no date as received] -- Ivan Plyushch, 
Ukrainian people's deputy, former speaker, and presidential 
candidate, replied to UNIAN's question at a news conference on 
16 June about his reaction to Vitaliy Masol's appointment as 
prime minister: "I spoke to Masol about a month ago or before, 
and he had a different attitude then. I do not know what 
pressure made Masol change his mind. I also do not know who 
needed to elect a prime minister 10 days before the presidential 
election, but I am not about to make a tragedy of this 
appointment. I know Masol as an experienced economist and 
statesman, and if I were to work with him, I think we would 
agree on a mutually complementary decision on this or that 
issue." 
  Asked by UNIAN to explain his differences with Leonid 
Kravchuk, recently coming to light in an ongoing indirect 
debate, Ivan Plyushch said: "I think Leonid Makarovych is the 
kind of politician who is very adept at adapting to public 
opinion. I believe a politician is a person who forms public 
opinion and leads it forward." 

</TEXT>

