<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gives News Conference on Visit </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Gives News Conference on Visit </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706094294 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1910 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1706094294 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>
<F P=105>  Ukrainian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Kiev [no date as received] -- The Israeli and 
Ukrainian foreign ministers, Shim'on Peres and Anatoliy Zlenko, 
held a joint news conference today at Ukraine's Ministry of 
Foreign Affairs. Zlenko, in particular, said the development of 
relations between the two countries has deep roots. "To many 
sons and daughters of the Jewish people, Ukraine has become a 
homeland encouraging the evolution of their talent. We regret 
that some of the best and most highly qualified professionals 
are leaving Ukraine. Our country does not object to the natural 
process of Jewish emigration as long as it proceeds in a 
civilized manner," Anatoliy Zlenko said. 
  The Ukrainian foreign minister underscored his country's 
readiness to contribute to ending confrontation in the Middle 
East region on a multilateral basis within the framework of the 
United Nations. 
  Shim'on Peres said this was his first visit to Ukraine and 
he 
could see differences between the situation in Ukraine and the 
way it is described by some of the mass media. He expressed the 
opinion that cooperation in the sphere of culture and business 
could be particularly fruitful. 
  As for Ukraine's role in settling Middle East issues, 
Shim'on 
Peres emphasized that Israel would welcome Ukraine's possible 
participation in the peace process in the Middle East region. 
  As far the Crimean issue is concerned, the Israeli foreign 
affairs minister underscored that Israel has already expressed 
its support for the Ukrainian Government's policy and that 
position remains unchanged. 
  Shim'on Peres also said that he will stay in Ukraine for one 
more day and on 17 June will visit Odessa where, he said, 
Israel's consulate is to open in the very near future. 

</TEXT>

