<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Troops, Black Sea Fleet Hold War Games </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Russian Troops, Black Sea Fleet Hold War Games </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706100294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0936 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1706100294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Albert Kochetkov] </F>
  [Text] Tbilisi June 17 TASS -- The Russian army group in 
Transcaucasia is holding a tactical military exercise on a 
regimental scale on a Black Sea coast near Batumi, Adjaria, on 
Friday. The aim of the exercise is to improve actions to rebuff 
an enemy landing party. 
  Marines are landing from Black Sea Fleet ships and 
helicopters, simulating air and artillery strikes, while 
defenders will hold out under the onslaught of superior enemy 
forces and defeat them. 
  President Eduard Shevardnadze and Georgian brass hats 
departed for the war games. Journalists interpreted this move 
as a pretext for a meeting with Adjarian leader Aslan Abashidze. 
  According to earlier reports, the latter temporarily 
combined 
the duties of parliament speaker (he dissolved parliament last 
year by his decree) with the duties of Adjarian premier. 
Reports say that this was done "at the suggestion of the heads 
of ministries and departments of the autonomous republic". 
  This move caused anxiety in Tbilisi which is concerned that 
Adjaria is increasingly disassociating itself from Georgia. 
  Despite the fact that the list of Russian journalists was 
compiled and agreed upon in good time, they got up at early 
hours and arrived at the Tbilisi airport in advance. 
  Nevertheless, they were removed from the plane, as ITAR-TASS 
learnt, "due to overload". Therefore, journalists have to be 
content with paltry reports received at the press centre of the 
Russian army group in Tbilisi. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

