<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Warns Crimea on Territorial `Integrity' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kravchuk Warns Crimea on Territorial `Integrity' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606180894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1711 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by ITAR-TASS correspondents Viktor Demidenko and </F>
Mikhail Melnik] 
  [Text] Odessa 16 June TASS -- "Ukrainian Armed Forces are 
able to defend their land, sovereignty and inviolability of 
state borders. In spite of the financial and material 
difficulties, Ukraine has a ready-for-combat army. It does not 
threaten anyone, however," Ukrainian President Leonid Kravchuk 
told servicemen of the First Ukrainian Aeromobile Division 
stationed in the Bolgrad District. 
  Touching upon "Crimean issues," Kravchuk emphasized that 
they 
should be solved only within the framework of Ukraine's 
Constitution. "Member states of the European Union and other 
countries support this position. Russian officialdom, including 
President Yeltsin, is of the same opinion. According to the 
acting Ukrainian Constitution and the trilateral agreement, 
Ukraine is a sovereign state and no one is entitled to break its 
integrity," Kravchuk said. 
  "We will not hamper the autonomous republic's drive for more 
independence. The official Kiev is ready to consider (Crimea's 
proposals to this effect). However, it should not be a matter 
of territory. The territory of our sovereign state is 
untouchable and no one should surpass the red line. We shall 
defend our integrity in accordance with the Constitution and 
shall not permit anyone to neglect our laws," Kravchuk 
emphasized. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

