<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-117 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Panov Comments on DPRK IAEA Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Panov Comments on DPRK IAEA Withdrawal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706111994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1024 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1706111994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russia's Deputy Foreign Minister Aleksandr Panov 
told Interfax that although Pyongyang's withdrawal from the 
International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] complicated matters, 
Russia was not withdrawing its call for an international 
conference on the Korean peninsula. 
  He said it was not Pyongyang's decision to withdraw from the 
IAEA and Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty that called for 
sanctions. Sanctions were not introduced against a country for 
this kind of decision, Panov said, because any country had the 
right to join a treaty or withdraw from it. 
  Panov went on to say that the international community was 
discontent with Pyongyang's failure to show good will and 
cooperate with the IAEA. As a result, the IAEA had failed to 
get a full picture of the North Korean nuclear program and had 
moved to raise the issue of sanctions. 
  Panov said that both Russia and its partners were interested 
in a negotiated solution of the problem. The Russian call for 
an international conference was gaining support, he said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-40549 </DOCNO>
