<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Atomic Energy Minister on DPRK Readiness To Make Bomb </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Atomic Energy Minister on DPRK Readiness To Make Bomb </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606192294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1655 
GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1606192294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 16 Jun -- North Korea is not yet ready to 
make an atom bomb in the opinion of Viktor Mikhaylov, the 
Russian Minister of Atomic Energy. It is too complicated a 
process, he said today when he was asked by an ITAR-TASS 
correspondent whether the DPRK will be able to produce enough 
plutonium to make atomic weapons. 
  As for the DPRK's departure from the IAEA, Viktor Mikhaylov 
considers that "this is more a cry from the heart on North 
Korea's part." He urged a dialogue between Russia and the 
United States on the issue of sanctions against the DPRK, 
observing that the country cannot be isolated, even if it 
announces its departure from the IAEA. "I think," he 
emphasized, "that on the North Korean issue dialogue will 
prevail and the DPRK will remain in the IAEA." 

</TEXT>

