<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Must Change Stand To Avoid Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK Must Change Stand To Avoid Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606142694 Moscow Radio Moscow World Service in English 
1110 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1606142694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow World Service </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Yuriy Soltan commentary] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang still has the time and the possibility to 
avoid sanctions. One thing only is needed for that: North Korea 
must change its present stand, which only generates more 
suspicion that the country already has or intends to have its 
own nuclear weapons. The Moscow proposal still holds about 
calling a many-sided conference to postpone sanctions. The 
conference might work out effective measures to safeguard the 
sovereignty and security of the two Korean states, that's on the 
one hand, and on the other to guarantee a nuclear-free status 
for the Korean peninsula. 
  North Korea is among many countries that considers such a 
conference feasible, but its conduct so far, especially its 
withdrawal from the IAEA, makes one think that the country opts 
for a path of upsetting the nuclear nonproliferation regimen. 
If that is the case the international community has no other 
choice but to introduce sanctions. Russia's foreign minister, 
Andrey Kozyrev, says such a development would be highly 
undesirable. 
  The United States draft resolution put before the United 
Nations Security Council offers an embargo on arms supplies to 
North Korea, curtailing financial transactions with it and 
suspending United Nations relief aid, but even if the draft is 
passed the sanctions will be phased, not introduced immediately. 
Pyongyang still has the time to prove to the world that its 
nuclear program is strictly peaceful. 
  As for brandishing arms, this is something fully applicable 
not only to Pyongyang but also to Washington and Seoul. That 
can have serious complications on the state of affairs on the 
Korean peninsula and in the rest of northeast Asia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

