<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary Assesses DPRK Withdrawal From IAEA </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Assesses DPRK Withdrawal From IAEA </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1606150494 Moscow Radio Moscow in Korean 1000 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1606150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Focus on Asia" program] </F>
  [Text] The DPRK's decision to withdraw from the IAEA has 
created new tensions with regard to the nuclear issue on the 
Korean peninsula. Our station commentator (Krichevskiy) writes: 
  Pyongyang has taken a new, very dangerous measure to beef up 
its confrontation with the international community. By so 
doing, Pyongyang tries to free itself from the IAEA's 
intervention with regard to the nuclear issue. However, this 
measure does not mean that the DPRK can ignore the IAEA's right 
to continue the inspections. This is because the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty [NPT] stipulates such a right. The DPRK 
is still a signatory of this treaty. 
  Pyongyang's decision immediately has caused a greater worry 
worldwide. A problem facing governments of many countries and 
the United Nations is what they should do. The United States 
more strongly demands that sanctions be imposed immediately. 
  Russia has begun to refer to sanctions more often. Russia 
does not like to see a country -- that violates the NPT and 
possesses nuclear weapons -- appear in its neighborhood. Russia 
does not like to see the situation along its border aggravated, 
either. 
  However, sanctions will inevitably bring such results. 
Therefore, Moscow has tenaciously pursued the possibility of 
imposing sanctions step by step and a proposal for convening an 
international conference attended by representatives of Russia, 
China, the United States, the DPRK, the ROK, the IAEA, and the 
United Nations. 
  There have been some results. After talking to U.S. 
President Clinton over telephone on 14 June, President Yeltsin 
said that they agreed to convene an international conference on 
the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula. They assigned the 
Russian Foreign Ministry and the U.S. Secretary of State to the 
task of linking the issue of holding of the international 
conference to the issue of imposing sanctions on the DPRK step 
by step. 
  China still plays an important role in coping with the 
crisis. China expresses a grave worry over the DPRK's decision 
and the future development of the situation on the Korean 
peninsula. Observers say that as it did before, Beijing opposes 
sanctions on the DPRK, demands the resumption of direct talks 
between Korea [choson] and the United States, and keeps silent 
on Russia's proposal for convening an international conference 
with China in attendance. In short, a complicated situation is 
prevailing. 
  However, there is still hope. This will be especially true 
if Pyongyang signals aspirations for resolving the complex knot, 
instead of bringing the issue to a deadlock. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
