<H3> <TI>   `Urgent State Affairs' Cited </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Urgent State Affairs' Cited </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706101294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0943 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1706101294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 17 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin failed to receive Vietnamese Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet 
on Friday because he has to solve urgent problems which have 
accumulated during the three days of his absence from Moscow, a 
high-ranking Kremlin official told TASS on Friday adding that 
"there are no politics behind the cancelled meeting". 
  He added that the meeting was planned only in a preliminary 
way. "As far as the Russian-Vietnamese documents are signed at 
the level and upon mutual agreement of the prime ministers of 
both countries, Boris Yeltsin who has been absent from Moscow 
for three days, is busy with urgent state affairs today", the 
official said. He did not elaborate. 
  Yeltsin spent three days touring the Russian Far East. 
  The TASS correspondent who was at the government Vnukovo-2 
Airport on Thursday when the president returned back to Moscow 
reported that the presidential escort waited for 45 minutes 
while Yeltsin was talking right at the entrance to the airport 
with Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev, chief of his staff Sergey 
Filatov and Interior Minister Viktor Yerin. There was a feeling 
that a lot of questions have been awaiting the president in 
Moscow since his departure. 

</TEXT>

