<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Camranh Naval Base To Be Resolved on `New Principles' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Camranh Naval Base To Be Resolved on `New Principles' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606195494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1907 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606195494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Andrey Bychkov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 16 TASS -- The problem of the use of the 
Camranh Base in Vietnam by the Russian Navy should be resolved 
on the basis of new principles in keeping with the spirit and 
demands of our time, Vietnamese Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet, who 
is on an official visit in Moscow, said in an interview with 
ITAR-TASS today. 
  "The crux of the matter is that," the Vietnamese leader 
recalled, "the agreement dates back to the period, when the 
Soviet Union still existed. That is the reason today we are 
signing a new interstate treaty with the Russian side, renewing 
and improving previous accords." Vo Van Kiet did not elaborate 
on details of the agreement, but he noted that the principles it 
is based on "will conform to conditions prevailing in our both 
countries today." 
  The Camranh base on the Vietnamese coast of the South China 
Sea was modernized during the years of war waged by U.S. forces 
in Vietnam. After America's retreat from Vietnam this facility 
was changed into a material-technical support centre for the 
Soviet Union's Navy. Currently the Camranh Bay is being used by 
Russia on the basis of the agreement signed by the former Soviet 
Union and Vietnam in 1981. The validity of the agreement 
expires in 2004. The strength of the servicing Russian personnel 
has been reduced to almost the one-fourth compared with that in 
1980, and coordination with the Vietnamese side has been 
converted to commercial basis. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

