<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev, Cotti Sign Cooperation Protocol </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev, Cotti Sign Cooperation Protocol </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1606173494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1709 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1606173494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Dmitriy Gorokhov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 16 TASS -- Russia and Switzerland are 
interested in seeing the Conference on Security and Cooperation 
in Europe (CSCE) play a "central and increasingly important role 
on the continent", Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev said 
at a press conference today. He was summing up the results of 
the talks held with Switzerland's head of federal department of 
foreign affairs Flavio Cotti in Moscow today. The head of the 
Russian Foreign Ministry and his Swiss counterpart signed a 
protocol on cooperation between foreign policy departments of 
the two countries. 
  Andrey Kozyrev called Bern's stand on international issues 
"responsible and constructive". He noted that the Russian 
foreign policy has been rid of "not only of the ideology 
syndrome, but of the complex of gigantomania as well". Kozyrev 
emphasised: In Moscow we have "learnt to value a partner, even 
if it seems to be a small country." "Switzerland, which is 
situated in the very centre of Europe, is our reliable friend 
and partner", he said, ascertaining that bilateral relations are 
quite intensively developing in all directions, including 
economic". The Russian foreign minister also noted personal 
friendly relations which he had established with Flavio Cotti 
during the head of the Russian foreign department's first 
official visit to Switzerland in 1992. 
  The Russian minister said that during today's talks they 
discussed regional problems. Kozyrev highly praised activities 
of Swiss diplomat and U.N. secretary-General's special envoy in 
Georgia Edouard Brunner. He called the latter's peace efforts 
an "example of concrete participation in settling the 
Georgian-Abkhazian conflict together with Russia." 
  Flavio Cotti thinks that Russia's peacemaking activities, 
naturally within the framework of international decisions, are 
in common interests". According to him, envoy Brunner also 
shares this conviction. The Swiss head of department of foreign 
affairs said that he agrees to Brunner's mission in Georgia 
being extended to an additional period, and he had recently 
spoken about it to U.N. Secretary-General Butrus Butrus-Ghali in 
Geneva. Taking into consideration the situation in Georgia, we 
are of the view that Brunner's mandate will be more directed 
towards organizational, legal and institutional issues. Besides 
this, in Cotti's opinion, it concerns the continuation of the 
traditionally peculiar to Switzerland diplomatic activities of 
mediation and rendering good services. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

