<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Denies Russia Not To Prolong DPRK Treaty </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev Denies Russia Not To Prolong DPRK Treaty </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706190394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1724 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1706190394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Dmitriy Gorokhov and </F>
Yuriy Kozlov] 
  [Text] Moscow June 17 TASS -- Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev has refuted claims that Russia will not prolong 
the treaty on friendship, cooperation and mutual assistance with 
the DPRK whose validity term expires in two years. No decisions 
to the effect have been taken, the minister told Duma deputies 
here today. 
  "The question of treaty prolongation will be raised in fall 
1995," said the minister. In his words, the Russian president 
will take a decision after possible consultations with the 
parliament. 
  A more updated interpretation of the treaty, including 
Article 1, with due account of today's realities is being 
discussed, he added. The thing is that some document wordings 
"reflected political thinking of two socialist states and 
include terms of that period -- on protection of common 
socialist values and so on. That is why, we certainly have a 
modern interpretation of the treaty text," said the minister. 

</TEXT>

