<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev on DPRK Threat to Russian Security </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kozyrev on DPRK Threat to Russian Security </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706185294 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1609 
GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706185294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Dmitriy Gorokhov and </F>
Yuriy Kozlov] 
  [Text] Moscow, 17 Jun -- The nuclear problem on the Korean 
Peninsula "contains a potential direct threat to the national 
security and state interests of the Russian Federation," Russian 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev said at the State Duma today. 
  First, he noted, what is involved here are steps to violate 
the nuclear weapons nonproliferation regime in a direct 
proximity to our borders, on the Korean Peninsula, where the 
situation is tense at times as it is. Therefore, the 
possibility of a nuclear state appearing in a zone of tension 
directly affects our security and interests. The second 
circumstance, in his words, is the fact that, apart from the 
DPRK, there is a "whole number of states that are on the 
threshold of adopting similar decisions aimed at acquiring 
nuclear weapons in one way or another." 
  "If one state," the minister continued, "is allowed to 
embark 
on this road and follow it through from start to finish, in 
other words, if one begins by violating the monitoring regime, 
then leaves the treaty and acquires nuclear weapons, there is no 
way other states could be kept away from this." But the "most 
unpleasant" thing, he stressed, is that the potential possessors 
of nuclear weapons are in conflict zones, moreover, the 
overwhelming majority of them are situated in a direct proximity 
to the Russian or CIS borders. Therefore, Kozyrev said, "what 
is important for us is not only the Korean issue but the 
precedent itself, and we cannot allow it to happen." 
  The international community has various means at its 
disposal 
with which to convince the DPRK to refrain from further hasty 
steps. First and foremost there are diplomatic contacts, which 
are now being exploited to the full, including those between 
Moscow and Pyongyang. The minister went on to recall Russia's 
proposal to convene an international conference on security and 
the nonnuclear status of the Korean Peninsula. 
  "One of the most extreme methods for exerting influence in 
such cases is to impose international sanctions in accordance 
with a decision by the Security Council," Andrey Kozyrev said. 
"It is quite obvious that if the DPRK goes as far as wrecking 
the nonproliferation regime and providing itself with nuclear 
weapons, then the international community, we included, will 
have no other option than to use the extreme method, that is, to 
impose sanctions." 
  Nevertheless, we believe that their introduction should be 
only gradual, the minister continued. "We should begin from the 
milder sanctions of a warning nature," Andrey Kozyrev said. 
"Considering the present circumstances, the Security Council 
should work in two directions: Preparing an international 
conference and, at the same time, defining the possible range of 
sanctions that may be applied if the DPRK fails to reconsider 
its policy." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

