<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Energy Minister Criticizes Proposed Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Energy Minister Criticizes Proposed Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1806012294 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 2230 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1806012294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Viktor Mikhaylov, Russian minister of atomic </F>
energy, by NHK Russian Bureau Chief Kazuo Kobayashi on 17 June; 
place not given; from NHK news -- Mikhaylov in Russian with 
Japanese translation provided in subtitles; translated from the 
subtitles] 
  [Text] Regarding North Korea's suspected nuclear arms 
development, Russian Minister of Atomic Energy Mikhaylov 
disclosed his belief on 17 June that North Korea needs more than 
10 years before being able to acquire nuclear weapons. He then 
criticized the movement to impose sanctions, saying that the 
international community should not isolate North Korea. 
  Energy Minister Mikhaylov explained his understanding of the 
attitude of North Korea, which rejected IAEA inspections, saying 
that the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] is making 
excessive demands on North Korea. On the current state of North 
Korea's nuclear arms development, he said as follows: 
  [Begin Mikhaylov recording] I believe that North Korea does 
not have nuclear weapons. It will take them from 10 to 20 
years, even if they begin producing nuclear weapons right now. 
[end recording] 
  [Begin Kobayashi recording] Russia is opposing the movement 
in the United States and other countries to impose sanctions 
against North Korea. Foreign Minister Kozyrev said that no 
prior consultations had been made with Russia regarding concrete 
proposals on the sanctions. However, the foreign minister's 
opposition and Energy Minister Mikhaylov's recent remarks 
reflect their twisted feelings that Russia is being treated 
lightly. 
  Russia is saying that not isolating North Korea is a better 
approach. This is the outcome of such a stance, and is Russia's 
appeal and advice to the international community. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

