<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentator Stresses International Meeting Importance </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentator Stresses International Meeting Importance </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2006022594 Moscow Radio Moscow in Korean 1200 GMT 16 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2006022594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Solton from "Today's World" program] </F>
  [Text] The UN Security Council began to discuss the U.S. 
draft resolution calling for sanctions on Korea because it 
rejected the international inspection of its nuclear sites and 
withdrew from the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA]. 
Station commentator Solton writes as follows. 
  Pyongyang still has a chance to avoid sanctions. This is 
possible if Korea changes its present position of encouraging 
suspicion that it already has a nuclear weapon or intends to 
have one. 
  The Moscow proposal for the convocation of a multilateral 
meeting is producing results. This meeting will be able to 
prevent sanctions. The international meeting can formulate 
measures for effective steps that will safeguard the sovereignty 
and security of the North and the South on one hand, and ensure 
the nonnuclear status of the Korean peninsula on the other hand. 
  Pyongyang and many other countries admit the appropriateness 
of the meeting, but the Korean action, particularly the 
withdrawal from the IAEA, leads people to suspect that it is 
leading to the North's withdrawal from the Nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty. If this is true, the international 
community has no alternative but to resort to sanctions. This 
development is very disadvantageous. Russian Foreign Minister 
Kozyrev agrees. 
  The resolution is to contain such measures as an arms 
embargo, restriction of financial transactions, and suspension 
of UN assistance. Yet even if this resolution is adopted, the 
sanctions will be taken not at one stroke but step by step. 
  Pyongyang has time to prove to all people that its nuclear 
project is peace-oriented. Wielding weapons affecting not only 
Pyongyang, but Washington and Seoul as well, can bring about 
consequences seriously aggravating the situation on the Korean 
peninsula and the entire Northeast Asian region . 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

