<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin, Clinton To Discuss G-7 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin, Clinton To Discuss G-7 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1906140794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1320 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1906140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Russian Prime-Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin is 
confident that next July the G-7 countries will grant Russia 
political membership of their club. The Big Seven are planning 
to hold a summit conference in Naples. 
  Talking to newsmen Sunday at a Moscow airport before 
boarding 
a flight for Milan where he is to attend a session of the World 
Gas Union, Chernomyrdin said there was a direct link between his 
trip to Milan and the Naples summit. He said he would discuss 
Russian membership of the G-7 club with his Italian counterpart 
Silvio Berlusconi who is to chair the Naples summit. 
  When he visited Washington on June 21, Chernomyrdin would 
discuss the issue with President Clinton. He felt there were no 
obstacles for Russian integration into the G-7 club. 
  According to Chernomyrdin Russia wait with a request for 
economic membership of the G-7 club. Moscow realized, he said, 
that it could be invited to work on political issues first and 
only then join G-7 economic efforts. 
  In Milan Chernomyrdin would be planning to discuss Russian- 
Italian relations with Prime-Minister Berlusconi and clear up 
where the two countries stood on the package of agreements he 
signed in Italy last January. 

</TEXT>

