<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Chernomyrdin To Discuss Trade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Chernomyrdin To Discuss Trade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1906140994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1231 GMT 19 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1906140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] As he visits the United States on June 21 to 26, 
Russian Prime-Minister Chernomyrdin will raise the problem of 
discriminatory restrictions in trade relations with Russia. 
  Talking to newsmen at Moscow's Vnukovo-2 airport before 
boarding a flight for Milan, Chernomyrdin said the United States 
had failed to meet its year-old pledge to lift all restrictions 
on trade with Russia. 
  According to Chernomyrdin, that although the United States 
suffered as much damage from the Jackson-Vanik amendment as 
Russia did, it kept stalling with moves to repeal it. [sentence 
as received] 
  Chernomyrdin said Russia wanted equitable relations with, 
and 
no special privileges from, the US. It would not tolerate 
discrimination, he said. Chernomyrdin hoped to find a solution 
to that problem during his visit to the United States. 
  His plans to visit the Livermore nuclear center proved, 
Chernomyrdin said, what progress Russian-US relations had made. 
Chernomyrdin will be the first Russian leader to visit the top 
secret center. 
  Chernomyrdin and the US leaders will be expected to focus on 
formerly "unmentionable" issues on the order of nuclear 
cooperation. 

</TEXT>

