<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Statement on Talks With SRV </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Ministry Statement on Talks With SRV </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1806134394 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0734 
GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1806134394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Bychkov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 18 June -- Russia and Vietnam consider the 
results of Vietnamese Prime Minister Vo Van Kiet's official 
visit to Moscow, which ended 17 June, on the whole to be 
successful. Russia and Vietnam converge in the opinion that the 
visit will contribute to future progress in Russo-Vietnamese 
relations, upgrading them significantly, says a report 
distributed to the press by the Russian Ministry of Foreign 
Affairs today. 
  The ministry notes that the treaty signed by Viktor 
Chernomyrdin, chairman of the Russian Federation Government, and 
Vo Van Kiet on the bases of friendly relations between the 
Russian Federation and the Socialist Republic of Vietnam 
"formulates the basic principles of cooperation between the two 
countries in light of the changes that have occurred both in 
Russia and Vietnam and in the international arena on the whole." 
  Also taking into account the three intergovernmental 
agreements concluded, which regulate capital investment problems 
and matters of cooperation in areas such as fishing and the 
agroindustrial complex, Russia and Vietnam now have 
approximately 15 intergovernmental documents, the result of work 
over the past two and a half years. 
  However, Moscow and Hanoi do not intend to stop there. The 
two countries' governments have thought it expedient to continue 
work on compiling a list of the treaties, agreements, and other 
intergovernmental documents concluded between the former USSR 
and Vietnam. It is planned to step up efforts to implement 
existing agreements in practice. 
  The fuel and power complex, including hydroelectricity, was 
described at the talks as being among the most promising areas 
of cooperation. The press release stresses that cooperation 
between individual regions of the two countries, particularly 
the Russian Far East and Vietnamese provinces, occupies an 
important place in the development of Russo-Vietnamese 
relations. 
  In discussing the international situation, the governmental 
heads of Russia and Vietnam confirmed that their views either 
coincided or were close on most of today's most urgent problems 
and called for the expansion of constructive cooperation aimed 
at creating a new, nonconfrontational system of interstate 
relations in the Asia- Pacific Ocean area and Southeast Asia, in 
particular. 
  Foreign Ministers Andrey Kozyrev and Nyugen Manh Cam went 
into greater detail on matters of international politics. They 
exchanged opinions on specific ways of coordinating the work of 
the Foreign Ministries "under the conditions of perceived 
changes for the better in the international climate." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

