<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Leaders Speak at Forum in Switzerland </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Leaders Speak at Forum in Switzerland </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1806072494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0651 GMT 18 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1806072494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Andrey Krasnoshchekov </F>
and Konstantin Pribytkov] 
  [Text] Crans-Montana (Switzerland) June 18 TASS -- The West 
should switch from aid to East European countries to mutually 
advantageous and equal cooperation with them, Speaker of the 
Byelorussian [Belarus] parliament Mechyslav Hryb said in an 
interview with ITAR-TASS here on Saturday. 
  According to the speaker, equality in trade and economic 
relations should mean, above all, "an increase or complete 
abrogation by the West of export quotas", since only this can 
evoke interest from both sides. 
  The idea of the need for establishing equal partnership 
between East and West European countries key-noted the first two 
days of the international forum in Crans-Montana devoted to 
East-West relations. Forum participants spoke about this at 
plenary meetings, seminars and at intervals between sessions. 
  In turn, Ivan Korotchenya, executive secretary of the 
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS), said in an interview 
with ITAR-TASS that the West's aid was inefficient to a great 
extent. For instance, the refusal by Byelorussia to take 
humanitarial aid has not virtually affected the situation in the 
republic in any way. 
  Therefore, he noted, relations between CIS republics and 
Western partners should be built on quite another basis: to 
develop contacts at all levels --from small enterprises to 
state-owned companies. "It is humiliating for our states to 
receive just aid," the executive secretary said. 
  The forum is discussing specific projects of cooperation. 
Korotchenya said that some delegations from CIS countries are 
already discussing proposals from potential Western partners. 
  Speaking at a plenary meeting, Swiss Economics Minister 
Jean-Pascal Delamuraz noted that success of international 
cooperation would be determined, above all, by stability in East 
European countries and consistency with which they would pursue 
reforms. 
  Interdependence of the countries in the old world has 
graphically demonstrated itself: The economic slump in the West 
negatively told on export opportunities from Eastern Europe. 
  Commercial relations is an important factor for economic 
growth. "Therefore, our aim should be the development of trade 
with the East and not aid," he summed up his speech. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS, Moldavian [Moldova] 
President 
Mircea Snegur called attention to the fact that the present 
forum considerably differs from other similar meetings: It 
examines not only economic but also political problems. 
  "Economic reforms and the development of relations are 
linked 
here directly with measures to ensure political stability on the 
continent," he stressed. This is of great interest for 
Moldavia, since "it is forced to overcome the consequences of a 
short armed conflict in 1992 up to this time". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

