<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Black Sea Fleet Vessels To Back Up Abkhaz Operations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Black Sea Fleet Vessels To Back Up Abkhaz Operations </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706202094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1816 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1706202094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A group of Black Sea Fleet vessels staying in the 
eastern part of the Black Sea began increased interaction with 
Russian troops in Western Georgia Friday. The operation is 
directed by the chief of the Black Sea Fleet command point, Rear 
Admiral Yuriy Nichik, the fleet's press center told Interfax. 
The goal of the peace-keeping action is to stabilize the 
situation in the region. 
  At present, preparation is being carried out for the 
deployment of Russian troops in the confrontation zone along the 
Inguri River to ensure security in the region. 
  In the meantime, another group of Black Sea Fleet vessels 
headed by the anti-submarine vessel Kerch left Sevastopol for 
the Greek island Corfu. The group's objective is to ensure the 
security of Russian President Boris Yeltsin as he attends the 
European Union summit on June 24-25. 
  The group is under command of the First Deputy Chief of the 
Black Sea Fleet staff, Rear Admiral Anatoliy Manchenko. 

</TEXT>

