<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow, Tel Aviv To Co-Produce, Sell Aircraft </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Moscow, Tel Aviv To Co-Produce, Sell Aircraft </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706194394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1658 GMT 17 Jun 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1706194394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Staroselskiy] </F>
  [Text] Moscow June 17 TASS -- Russia and Israel have agreed 
to develop and sell on the world market a new aircraft - the 
YAK-48- Galaxy. This was announced by President of the Russian 
Chamber of Commerce and Industry Stanislav Smirnov today. He 
praised direct contacts between entrepreneurs of the two 
countries established at the exhibition Israel-94 in Moscow. 
  Chairman of the Council of Directors and Chief Designer of 
the Yakovlev Design bureau Aleksandr Dondukov explained that the 
YAK-48 is an eight-seat government and business aircraft with a 
unique range of 6,800 kilometers. The contract signed between 
Russia and Israel provides for the development of the project on 
the basis of advanced Russian technologies. It will be possible 
to use engines and electronics made in third countries. The new 
aircraft will be partially assembled and sold by Israel, which 
is now controlling 25 percent of the world market for this 
category of planes. 
  Dondukov said that the first YAK-48 will be ready in 1995, 
and its mass production and sale on the world market will begin 
in 1997. 

</TEXT>

