<DOCNO> FBIS4-40637 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov118_d_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-118 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  17 Jun 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Regional Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tatarastan, Komi Sign Cooperation Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Tatarastan, Komi Sign Cooperation Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD1706205194 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1900 GMT 
17 Jun 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1706205194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>
<F P=105>  Russian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Today, Tatarstan President Mintimer Shaymiyev and 
Yuriy Spiridonov, head of the Komi Republic, ceremonially signed 
an agreement on friendship and cooperation in Kazan. Here is 
our Kazan correspondent Zhaudat Aminov. 
  [Aminov] At a news conference given straight after the 
signing of the agreement it was said that an agreement of this 
kind strengthens Russia as a great and distinctive state that 
contains many curious phenomenon. 
  Boris Yeltsin is perhaps the only person in Russia's 
leadership who really understands what a federation is, Yuriy 
Spiridonov said. It is good that he is president, Mintimer 
Shaymiyev said, agreeing. Both leaders believe that the time is 
not far off when the federation treaty issue will have to be 
tackled again and the federation will be built up from below, 
taking into account the interests of the republics and the 
regions. 
  Russia's oil-producing regions, which include Tatarstan and 
Komi, today founded a consortium to jointly manage the export of 
fuel. The agreement promises to be mutually advantageous. 
  Both leaders agreed on closer cooperation at the Federation 
Council level, too, although they were of the opinion that that 
body had yet to assume a proper role and did not have any real 
influence on the situation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
